THE date of Calpurnius is uncertain, but he is supposed on good grounds to have lived in the time of the Emperor Nero (54—68 A. D.). ln older editions eleven Eclogues were assigned to him, but the last four are probably by Neme— sianus, who flourished towards the end of the third century. Both poets have closely imitated Virgi13 Nemesianus has also taken Calpurnius as his model, especially in his second Eclogue, the ninth of the whole series.
